07972nam a22007695i 9780824892258DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222023hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248922587 a10.1515/97808248922582doi  a(DE-B1597)645000  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aHIS0530002bisacsh00aMigrant Ecologies :bEnvironmental Histories of the Pacific World /ced. by James Beattie, Ryan Tucker Jones, Edward Dallam Melillo, Anand A. Yang, Kieko Matteson. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2022] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b28 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives on the Global Past00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMap of the Pacific World -- tPreface -- tIntroduction Environmental Histories of the Pacific World -- t1 Long-Distance Animal Migration and the Creation of a Pacific World: A History in Three Species -- t2 Many Diasporas: People, Nature, and Movement in Pacific History -- t3 Chinese Resource Frontiers, Environmental Change, and Entrepreneurship in the South Pacific, 1790s-1920s -- t4 The Third Vector: Pacific Pathogens, Colonial Disease Ecologies, and Native American Epidemics North of Mexico -- t5 Sentiment and Gore: Whaling the Pacific World -- t6 Changes on the Plantation: An Environmental History of Colonial Samoa -- t7 "One Extensive Garden"? Citrus Schemes and Land Use in the Cook Islands, 1900-1970 -- t8 Settler-Colonialism, Ecology, and Expropriation of Ainu Mosir A Transnational Perspective -- t9 Pearl of the Empire Conservation, Commerce, and Science in the Tuamotu Archipelago -- t10 From Boki's Beans to Kona Coffee The 'Ōiwi (Native) Roots of an Exotic Species -- t11 Maunalua: Shifting Nomenclatures and Spatial Reconfiguration in Hawaii Kai -- t12 Bait and Switch: Tuna Wars, Territorial Seas, and the Eco-geography of the Eastern Tropical Pacific, 1931-1982 -- t13 Wintering in the South: Birds, Place, and Flows -- t14 Bravo for the Pacific: Nuclear Testing, Ecosystem Ecology, and the Emergence of Direct Action Environmentalism -- t15 A Pacific Anthropocene -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aMigrant Ecologies: Environmental Histories of the Pacific World is the first volume explicitly dedicated to the environmental history of Earth's largest ocean. Covering nearly one-third of the planet, the Pacific Ocean is remarkable for its diverse human and non-human inhabitants, their astounding long-distance migrations over time, and their profound influences on other parts of the world. This book creates an understanding of the past, present, and futures of the lands, seas, peoples, practices, microbes, animals, plants, and other natural forces that shape the Pacific. It effectively argues for the existence of an interconnected Pacific World environmental history, as well as for the Pacific Ocean as a necessary framework for understanding that history.The fifteen chapters in this comprehensive collection, written by leading experts from across the globe, span a vast array of topics, from disease ecology and coffee cultivation to nuclear testing and whaling practices. They explore regions stretching from the Tuamotu Archipelago in the south Pacific to the Kamchatka Peninsula in the far north, resisting the depiction of the Pacific as isolated and uninhabited. What unites these diverse contributions is a concern for how the people, places, and non-human beings of the Pacific World have been shaped by, and have in turn modified, their oceanic realm. Building on a recent renaissance in Pacific history, these chapters make a powerful argument for the importance of the Pacific World as a coherent unit of analysis and a valuable lens through which to examine past, ongoing, and emerging environmental issues. By showcasing surprising and innovative perspectives on the environmental histories of the peoples and ecosystems in and around the Pacific Ocean, this work adds to current conversations and debates about the Pacific World and offers myriad opportunities for further discussions, both inside and outside of the classroom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Oceania.2bisacsh1 aBeattie, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeattie, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCavert, William Matt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavert, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutting-Jones, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDallam Melillo, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDroessler, Holger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirano, Katsuya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Ryan Tucker, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Ryan Tucker, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMadley, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatteson, Kieko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcNeill, J. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcNeill, John R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMelillo, Edward Dallam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMelillo, Edward Dallam, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/voca